<br>
Anybody that prefers Robert Jordan to J. R. R. Tolkien has a tin ear.  <br>
<br>
I read the (Endless) Wheel of Time up to the seventh book, and I came to the same conclusion as Fritz.  A better name for this series is the Waste of Time -- the man has little grasp of how to advance a plot, and just bogs it down in soul-crushing detail.  The story's not interesting enough to compel me to read any more.  What you call &quot;character development&quot; I call surplusage -- I don't find the characters particularly &quot;well developed&quot; for all the verbiage being used to describe them.  I didn't feel at all connected to any of the characters, and I found some of them (especially the women) unrealistic and implausible.  (A friend likened Jordan's female characters to those found in Piers Anthony's &quot;work&quot; ... I was forced to agree.)<br>
<br>
Tolkien's prose was, often, beautiful.  (And Lord Dunsany, the grandfather of fantasy, is amazing.)  Jordan's is leaden, plodding, and, well, prosaic.  In my opinion, Robert Jordan is an overrated hack who makes far more money than he deserves.  If he had finished this series at three or four books, it would still be mediocre; to stretch it to ten or more is a literary crime.  <br>
<br>
Before anybody says, &quot;Well, you read seven of them, obviously you didn't hate them as much as you claim,&quot; are you saying you've never finished a bad series just because you might as well see how it ends?  <br>
<br>
Of the series listed, I'd have to say first, Tolkien, second, Thomas Covenant, for having the best single character out of any of the listed books.  I'd have to rank Amber as third, McAffrey as fourth (although I liked all four of those series) and Jordan a distant fifth, tied with the instructions that came with my VCR.<br>
 <br>
(And I'd have to give an honorable mention to George R. R. Martin for being the best active fantasy writer at the moment.  &quot;A Song of Ice and Fire&quot; is so superior to Jordan it's almost funny.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugorgash.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gorgash</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.shadowguard.org/resources/skull15-2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 66<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/24/01 6:25:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=33.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Which fantasy series do you like the most?</span><hr size=1> Personally I despised the character of Thomas Covenant, hated him!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
